# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astronomer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] Dallal received his bachelor's degree in engineering from the American University of Beirut.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] He worked in the aviation industry before earning his master's and doctorate from Columbia University.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] Dallal taught at Stanford University, Yale University, and Smith College before joining the Georgetown University faculty, where he was an associate professor of Arabic and Islamic studies and Chair of Georgetown's Arabic and Islamic Studies department.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] His research focused on the history of learning and the history of sciences in Islamic societies as well as Islamic thoughts and movements.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] Terry Lectureship at Yale University in 2008, titled *Islam, Science, and the Challenge of History*.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] Dallal served as the provost of the American University of Beirut from 2009 to 2015 before returning to teach history at the university.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] He was named dean of Georgetown University in Qatar in 2017.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] In 2021, Dallal was named 13th President of The American University in Cairo.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] He is the first Arab to serve as president of the university.
[src:astronomer/ahmad-dallal] Dallal speaks both English and Arabic, and can also speak Persian, German and French.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers do not use the field of astronomy as their primary source of income or support, as well as typically having no professional degree in astrophysics or advanced academic training in the subject.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Most amateur astronomers are hobbyists, while others have a high degree of experience in astronomy and may often assist and work alongside professional astronomers.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Many astronomers have studied the sky throughout history in an amateur framework; however, since the beginning of the twentieth century, professional astronomy has become a clearly distinguished activity from amateur astronomy and associated activities.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers typically view the sky at night, when most celestial objects and astronomical events are visible, but others observe during the daytime by viewing the Sun and solar eclipses.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Some observe the sky using nothing more than their eyes or binoculars, while more dedicated amateurs often use portable telescopes or telescopes situated in their private or club observatories.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] However, light pollution has made amateur astronomy increasingly difficult to observe celestial objects, as sky glow washes out darkness and minimizes visibility.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateurs commonly join amateur astronomical societies, which can advise, educate, or guide individuals towards ways of finding and observing celestial objects.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Astronomical societies also promote the science of astronomy among the general public.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Collectively, amateur astronomers observe a variety of celestial objects and phenomena.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Common targets of amateur astronomers include the Sun, the Moon, planets, stars, comets, meteor showers, and a variety of deep sky objects such as star clusters, galaxies, and nebulae.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers purse their work in order to educate the public, make contributions to the scientific world, and express their passion.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Many amateurs like to specialize in observing particular objects, types of objects, or types of events which interest them.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] One branch of amateur astronomy, amateur astrophotography, involves the taking of photos of the night sky.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Astrophotography has become more popular with the introduction of far easier to use equipment including digital cameras, DSLR cameras and relatively sophisticated purpose built high quality CCD cameras and CMOS cameras.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Most amateur astronomers work at visible wavelengths, but a small minority experiment with wavelengths outside the visible spectrum.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] An early pioneer of radio astronomy was Grote Reber, an amateur astronomer who constructed the first purpose-built radio telescope in the late 1930s to follow up on the discovery of radio wavelength emissions from space by Karl Jansky.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Non-visual amateur astronomy includes the use of infrared filters on conventional telescopes, and also the use of radio telescopes.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Some amateur astronomers use home-made radio telescopes, while others use radio telescopes that were originally built for astronomical research but have since been made available for use by amateurs.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The One-Mile Telescope is one such example.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Sidewalk astronomy — the practice of setting up telescopes for public viewing — aims at educating and engaging the public with astronomy.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] In addition to increasing interest in astronomy and science in general, sidewalk astronomy raises awareness of light pollution issues.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The history of amateur astronomy dates back to early civilizations where the practice of observing celestial objects became a device that assisted in predicting atmospheric patterns to help enable proactive decisions on developing agriculture.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Civilizations like the Babylonians, Chaldeans, and ancient Egyptians created calendars, predicted eclipse dates, and separated day and night through ancient amateur astronomers using simple tools and the naked eye to track celestial bodies.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Popularizing in the mid-nineteenth century, amateur astronomy gained millions of participants evolving from wealthy "Grand Amateurs" and the more accessible equipment after World War II.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers use a range of instruments to study the sky, depending on a combination of their interests and resources.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] To further improve studying the visual and non-visual part of the spectrum, amateur astronomers go to rural areas to get away from light pollution.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Commercial telescopes are available, new and used, but it is also common for amateur astronomers to build (or commission the building of) their own custom telescopes.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Some people even focus on amateur telescope making as their primary interest within the hobby of amateur astronomy.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Although specialized and experienced amateur astronomers tend to acquire more specialized and powerful equipment over time, relatively simple equipment is often preferred for certain tasks.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Binoculars, for instance, although generally of lower power than the majority of telescopes, also tend to provide a wider field of view and are more portable, which is preferable for looking at some objects in the night sky.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Recent smartphone models have a "night mode" option when taking pictures that allows users to increase exposure, which refers to the period of time the picture is being taken.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] This optimizes focus on light in the frame which is why it is used primarily at night.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Beginner telescopes, commonly used by amateur astronomers to observe celestial objects in more detail, are a more powerful tool compared to other amateur equipment such as binoculars.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers often use four main types of optical telescopes: reflectors, refractors, hybrid, and Dobsonian telescopes.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Reflector telescopes utilize mirrors while refractors use lenses, these combine to create the hybrid telescope, which uses a combination of both mirrors and lenses.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The Dobsonian is a type of reflector with the addition of a base or mount.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] GOTO telescopes have become more popular since the 1980s as technology has improved and prices have been reduced.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] With these computer-driven telescopes, the user typically enters the name of the item of interest and the mechanics of the telescope point the telescope towards that item automatically.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] They have several notable advantages for amateur astronomers intent on research.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] For example, GOTO telescopes tend to be faster for locating items of interest than star hopping, allowing more time for studying of the object.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] GOTO also allows manufacturers to add equatorial tracking to mechanically simpler alt-azimuth telescope mounts, allowing them to produce an overall less expensive product.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] GOTO telescopes usually have to be calibrated using alignment stars to provide accurate tracking and positioning.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Several telescope manufacturers have recently developed telescope systems that are calibrated with the use of built-in GPS, decreasing the time it takes to set up a telescope at the start of an observing session.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] This enables anyone to control a telescope a great distance away in a dark location.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The observer can image through the telescope using CCD cameras.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The digital data collected by the telescope is then transmitted and displayed to the user by means of the Internet.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] An example of a digital remote telescope operation for public use via the Internet is the Bareket Observatory, and there are telescope farms in New Mexico, Australia and Atacama in Chile.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers also use star charts that, depending on experience and intentions, may range from simple planispheres through to star atlases with detailed charts of the entire night sky.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] A range of astronomy software is also available and used by amateur astronomers, including software that generates maps of the sky, software to assist with astrophotography, observation scheduling software, and software to perform various calculations pertaining to astronomical phenomena.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] To find a celestial object in a telescope equipped with a DSC computer, one does not need to look up the specific RA and Dec coordinates in a book or other resource, and then adjust the telescope to those numerical readings.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Rather, the object is chosen from the electronic database, which causes distance values and arrow markers to appear in the display that indicate the distance and direction to move the telescope.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The telescope is moved until the two angular distance values reach zero, indicating that the telescope is properly aligned.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] When both the RA and Dec axes are thus "zeroed out", the object should be in the eyepiece.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Many DSCs, like go-to systems, can also work in conjunction with laptop sky programs.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Computerized systems provide the further advantage of computing coordinate precession.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Traditional printed sources are subtitled by the *epoch* year, which refers to the positions of celestial objects at a given time to the nearest year (e.g., J2005, J2007).
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Most such printed sources have been updated for intervals of only about every fifty years (e.g., J1900, J1950, J2000).
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Computerized sources, on the other hand, are able to calculate the right ascension and declination of the "epoch of date" to the exact instant of observation.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers often like to keep records of their observations, which usually takes the form of an observing log.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Observing logs typically record details about which objects were observed and when, as well as describing the details that were seen.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Sketching is sometimes used within logs, and photographic records of observations have also been used in recent times.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The information gathered is used to help studies and interactions between amateur astronomers in yearly gatherings.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Although not professional information or credible, it is a way for the hobby lovers to share their new sightings and experiences.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The advent of mobile applications for use in smartphones has led to the creation of many dedicated apps.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] These apps allow any user to easily locate celestial objects of interest by simply pointing the smartphone device in that direction in the sky.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] These apps make use of the inbuilt hardware in the phone, such as GPS location and gyroscope.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Useful information about the pointed object like celestial coordinates, the name of the object, its constellation, etc. are provided for a quick reference.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Some paid versions give more information.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] These apps are gradually getting into regular use during observing, for the alignment process of telescopes.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The popularity of imaging among amateurs has led to large numbers of web sites being written by individuals about their images and equipment.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Much of the social interaction of amateur astronomy occurs on mailing lists or discussion groups.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Discussion group servers host numerous astronomy lists.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] A great deal of the commerce of amateur astronomy, the buying and selling of equipment, occurs online.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Many amateurs use online tools to plan their nightly observing sessions, using tools such as the Clear Sky Chart.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] While a number of interesting celestial objects are readily identified by the naked eye, sometimes with the aid of a star chart, many others are so faint or inconspicuous that technical means are necessary to locate them.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Although many methods are used in amateur astronomy, most are techniques that are adaptations of core practices.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Amateur astronomers engage in many imaging techniques including film, DSLR, LRGB, and CCD astrophotography.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] DSLR (digital single-lens reflex) cameras, such as the Canon EOS 60D camera, provide a cost-effective, consumer-grade alternative to CCDs, capable of achieving ideal outcomes for MAD (median absolute deviation).
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] LRGB produce high-quality, cleaner images, allowing amateur astronomers to acquire fine color detail by combining a RGB color images and greyscale images.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] CCD cameras are widely used due to their fast exposures, sensitivity, dynamic range, less hardware, and linear response, allowing amateur astronomers to capture vague celestial objects.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Because CCD imagers are linear, image processing may be used to subtract away the effects of light pollution, which has increased the popularity of astrophotography in urban areas.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Narrowband filters may also be used to minimize light pollution.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] In recent times, increasing light pollution, radio interference, and satellite activity have had a negative effect on the outcomes of amateur astronomers' observations and work, limiting their potential contributions or findings of scientific discoveries.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Urban lighting has had particularly detrimental effects on amateur astronomers by light trespass compromising their observatories and ruining the correct lighting conditions for photographic observations.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Although not the *main* goal of amateur astronomers, scientific research is possible, and many amateurs successfully contribute to the knowledge base of astronomy.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Astronomy is sometimes promoted as one of the few remaining sciences for which amateurs can still contribute useful data.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] To recognize this, the Astronomical Society of the Pacific annually gives Amateur Achievement Awards for significant contributions to astronomy by amateurs.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The majority of scientific contributions by amateur astronomers are in the area of data collection.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] In particular, this applies where large numbers of amateur astronomers with small telescopes are more effective than the relatively small number of large telescopes that are available to professional astronomers.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Several organizations, such as the American Association of Variable Star Observers and the British Astronomical Association, exist to help coordinate these contributions.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] With more advanced equipment, but still cheap in comparison to professional setups, amateur astronomers can measure the light spectrum emitted from astronomical objects, which can yield high-quality scientific data if the measurements are performed with due care.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] A relatively recent role for amateur astronomers is searching for overlooked phenomena (e.g., Kreutz Sungrazers) in the vast libraries of digital images and other data captured by Earth and space based observatories, much of which is available over the Internet.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] In the past and present, amateur astronomers have played a major role in discovering new comets.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] The introduction of projects such as the Lincoln Near-Earth Asteroid Research and Near Earth Asteroid Tracking projects has meant that most comets are now discovered by automated systems long before it is possible for amateurs to see them.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] There are a large number of amateur astronomical societies around the world, that serve as a meeting point for those interested in amateur astronomy.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Members range from active observers with their own equipment to "armchair astronomers" who are simply interested in the topic.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Societies range widely in their goals and activities, which may depend on a variety of factors such as geographic spread, local circumstances, size, and membership.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] For example, a small local society located in dark countryside may focus on practical observing and star parties, whereas a large one based in a major city might have numerous members but be limited by light pollution and thus hold regular indoor meetings with guest speakers instead.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] Major national or international societies generally publish their own academic journal or newsletter, and some hold large multi-day meetings akin to a scientific conference or convention.
[src:astronomer/amateur-astronomy] They may also have sections devoted to particular topics, such as lunar observation or amateur telescope making.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] An **amateur** (from French 'one who loves') is generally considered a person who pursues an avocation independent from their source of income.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Amateurs and their pursuits are also described as popular, informal, self-taught, user-generated, DIY, and hobbyist.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Historically, the amateur was considered to be the ideal balance between pure intent, open mind, and the interest or passion for a subject.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] That ideology spanned many different fields of interest.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] It may have its roots in the ancient Greek philosophy of amateur athletes competing in the Olympics.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The ancient Greek citizens spent most of their time in other pursuits, but competed according to their natural talents and abilities.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The "gentleman amateur" was a phenomenon among the gentry of Great Britain from the 17th century until the 20th century.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] With the start of the Age of Reason, with people thinking more about how the world works around them, (see science in the Age of Enlightenment), things like the cabinets of curiosities, and the writing of the book *The Christian Virtuoso*, started to shape the idea of the gentleman amateur.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] He was vastly interested in a particular topic, and studied, observed, and collected things and information on his topic of choice.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The Royal Society in Great Britain was generally composed of these "gentleman amateurs", and is one of the reasons science today exists the way it does.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] A few examples of these gentleman amateurs are Francis Bacon, Isaac Newton, and Sir Robert Cotton, 1st Baronet, of Connington.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Amateurism can be seen in both a negative and positive light.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Since amateurs often lack formal training and are self-taught, some amateur work may be considered sub-par.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] For example, amateur athletes in sports such as basketball, baseball, or football are regarded as possessing a lower level of ability than professional athletes.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] On the other hand, an amateur may be in a position to approach a subject with an open mind (as a result of the lack of formal training) and in a financially disinterested manner.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] An amateur who dabbles in a field out of interest rather than as a profession, or possesses a general but superficial interest in any art or a branch of knowledge, is often referred to as a dilettante.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Through most of the 20th century the Olympics allowed only amateur athletes to participate and this amateur code was strictly enforced, Jim Thorpe was stripped of track and field medals for having taken expense money for playing baseball in 1912.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Later on, the nations of the Communist Bloc entered teams of Olympians who were all nominally students, soldiers, or working in a profession, but many of whom were in reality paid by the state to train on a full-time basis.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Near the end of the 1960s, the Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (CAHA) felt their amateur players could no longer be competitive against the Soviet team's full-time athletes and the other constantly improving European teams.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] They pushed for the ability to use players from professional leagues but met opposition from the International Ice Hockey Federation (IIHF) and the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:astronomer/amateurs] At the IIHF Congress in 1969, the IIHF decided to allow Canada to use nine non-NHL professional hockey players at the 1970 World Championships in Montreal and Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The decision was reversed in January 1970 after IOC President Avery Brundage said that ice hockey's status as an Olympic sport would be in jeopardy if the change was made.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] In response, Canada withdrew from all international ice hockey competitions and officials stated that they would not return until "open competition" was instituted.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Günther Sabetzki became president of the IIHF in 1975 and helped to resolve the dispute with the CAHA.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] In 1976, the IIHF agreed to allow "open competition" between all players in the World Championships.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] However, NHL players were still not allowed to play in the Olympics, because of the unwillingness of the NHL to take a break mid-season and the IOC's amateur-only policy.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Before the 1984 Winter Olympics, a dispute formed over what made a player a professional.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The IOC had adopted a rule that made any player who had signed an NHL contract but played less than ten games in the league eligible.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] However, the United States Olympic Committee maintained that any player contracted with an NHL team was a professional and therefore not eligible to play.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The IOC held an emergency meeting that ruled NHL-contracted players were eligible, as long as they had not played in any NHL games.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] This made five players on Olympic rosters—one Austrian, two Italians and two Canadians—ineligible.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Players who had played in other professional leagues—such as the World Hockey Association—were allowed to play.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Canadian hockey official Alan Eagleson stated that the rule was only applied to the NHL and that professionally contracted players in European leagues were still considered amateurs.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Murray Costello of the CAHA suggested that a Canadian withdrawal was possible.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] In 1986, the IOC voted to allow all athletes to compete in Olympic Games starting in 1988, but let the individual sport federations decide if they wanted to allow professionals.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The act caused the breakup of the Amateur Athletic Union as a wholesale sports governing body at the Olympic level).
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Olympic regulations regarding amateur status of athletes were eventually abandoned in the 1990s with the exception of wrestling, where the amateur fight rules are used because professional wrestling is largely staged with predetermined outcomes.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Starting from the 2016 Summer Olympics, professionals were allowed to compete in boxing, though amateur fight rules are still used for the tournament.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Many amateurs make valuable contributions in the field of computer programming through the open source movement.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Amateur dramatics is the performance of plays or musical theater, often to high standards, but lacking the budgets of professional West End or Broadway performances.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Astronomy, chemistry, history, linguistics, and the natural sciences are among the fields that have benefited from the activities of amateurs.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Gregor Mendel was an amateur scientist who never held a position in his field of study.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Radio astronomy was founded by Grote Reber, an amateur radio operator.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Radio itself was greatly advanced by Guglielmo Marconi, a young Italian man who started out by tinkering with a coherer and a spark coil as an amateur electrician.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] Pierre de Fermat was a highly influential mathematician whose primary vocation was law.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] In the 2000s and 2010s, the distinction between amateur and professional has become increasingly blurred, especially in areas such as computer programming, music and astronomy.
[src:astronomer/amateurs] The term amateur professionalism, or pro-am, is used to describe these activities.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The **American Astronomical Society** (**AAS**, sometimes spoken as "double-A-S") is an American society of professional astronomers and other interested individuals, headquartered in Washington, DC.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The primary objective of the AAS is to promote the advancement of astronomy and closely related branches of science, while the secondary purpose includes enhancing astronomy education and providing a political voice for its members through lobbying and grassroots activities.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Its current mission is to enhance and share humanity's scientific understanding of the universe as a diverse and inclusive astronomical community.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The society was founded in 1899 through the efforts of George Ellery Hale.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The constitution of the group was written by Hale, George Comstock, Edward Morley, Simon Newcomb and Edward Charles Pickering.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] These men, plus four others, were the first Executive Council of the society; Newcomb was the first president.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The AAS name of the society was not finally decided until 1915, previously it was the "Astronomical and Astrophysical Society of America".
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] One proposed name that preceded this interim name was "American Astrophysical Society".
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The membership includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers and others whose research interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects now comprising contemporary astronomy.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The annual meeting of the AAS is held in the spring and constitutes the largest gathering of astronomers, numbering over 3,000 in 2023.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] In 2019 three AAS members were selected into the tenth anniversary class of TED Fellows.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] In January 2025, AAS published a statement calling on nations to ban advertising from space that can be seen from the ground amid growing concern around the launch obtrusive space advertising payloads.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The AAS is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The membership includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers and others whose research interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects comprising contemporary astronomy.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The society offers several classes of membership and affiliation.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Full Members must meet at least two of three criteria: possessing a graduate degree in astronomy or a related science, receiving the nomination of a current Full Member, or having placed a refereed publication in a recognised international journal.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Until 2018, admission as a Full Member required nomination by two existing Full Members; that year the society restructured its membership classes, broadening eligibility to include holders of master's degrees and introducing new affiliate categories.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Other membership classes include Graduate Student Members, Undergraduate Student Members (also open to high-school students), International Affiliates for astronomers residing outside the United States, Amateur Affiliates, and Alumni Affiliates for former members who have left the field.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] As of 2025, the AAS has approximately 8,200 members across all categories.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The society is a member society of the American Institute of Physics.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The AAS established its Fellows program in 2019 to recognise members for achievement and extraordinary service to the field of astronomy and the society.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The inaugural class, designated by the AAS Board of Trustees, included 232 Legacy Fellows.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] New fellows are elected annually thereafter.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Because the field of astronomy is diverse, several divisions have been formed each of which promotes and enables a different branch of astronomy or astronomy-related science as well as working within the overall charter of the AAS.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Many of the divisions hold separate meetings in addition to meeting with the main group.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] Similar prizes are awarded by AAS divisions.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] The AAS also manages an International Travel Grant program, which any astronomer working in the US may apply to for travel to international astronomy-related conferences and other smaller grant and award programs.
[src:astronomer/american-astronomical-society] American Astronomical Society won the 2020 Webby People's Voice Award for Association in the category Web.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:astronomer/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Greek astronomy was influenced heavily by Babylonian astronomy, as well as Egyptian astronomy to a lesser degree.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In later centuries, Greek-language astronomical works were translated into other languages, enabling their further spread.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Most notably, Arabic translations of these works benefitted astronomers and mathematicians throughout the Muslim world during the Middle Ages.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Many Greek astronomical texts are known only by name, and perhaps by a description or quotations.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Some elementary works have survived because they were largely non-mathematical and suitable for use in schools.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Books in this class include the *Phaenomena* of Euclid and two works by Autolycus of Pitane.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Three important textbooks, written shortly before Ptolemy's time, were written by Cleomedes, Geminus, and Theon of Smyrna.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Books by Roman authors like Pliny the Elder and Vitruvius contain some information on Greek astronomy.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The most important primary source is the *Almagest*, since Ptolemy refers to the work of many of his predecessors.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The main features of Archaic Greek cosmology are shared with those found in ancient Near Eastern cosmology.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] They include (a flat) Earth, a Heaven (firmament) where the Sun, Moon, and stars are located, an outer ocean surrounding the inhabited human realm, and the netherworld (Tartarus), the first three of which corresponded to the gods Ouranos, Gaia, and Oceanus (or Pontos).
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Thales of Miletus was a primary figure of the Ionian school of Greek philosophy.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] He is also usually credited for initiating the tradition of Greek science in modern historiography, although others have challenged this attribution.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Like his predecessors, such as Hesiod and Homer, Thales accepted that the Earth was flat and rests on a primordial and endless ocean.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] He also notably proposed that the universe was fundamentally composed of water.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Anaximander, a student of Thales and another prominent member of the Ionian school, realized that the northern sky seems to turn around the North star, which led him to the concept of a Celestial sphere around Earth.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] And, as the sky seems to vary with latitude, he also considered that Earth's surface may be curved as well.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] However, he incorrectly thought that the Earth was a cylinder as opposed to a sphere.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The notion of a spherical Earth first found an audience with the Pythagoreans, but this was due to philosophical as opposed to scientific reasons: the sphere was considered a perfectly geometrical figure.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The first book of the Almagest included a chapter dedicated to the defense of each of these assumptions and refuting alternative positions, using both philosophy and astronomical observation.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The term "planet" comes from the Greek term πλανήτης (*planētēs*), meaning "wanderer", as ancient astronomers noted how certain points of lights moved across the sky in relation to the other stars (which appear fixed).
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Five planets can be seen with the naked eye: Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn, the Greek names being Hermes, Aphrodite, Ares, Zeus and Cronus.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Early Greek astronomers thought that the evening and morning appearances of Venus represented two different objects, calling it *Hesperus* ("evening star") when it appeared in the western evening sky and *Phosphorus* ("light-bringer") when it appeared in the eastern morning sky.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] They eventually came to recognize that both objects were the same planet.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Credit is variously attributed to Pythagoras or Parmenides for this discovery.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Eudoxus is typically thought to have standardized the names of the constellations.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The earliest extant description of the constellations, the *Phaenomena* of Aratus (270 BC), is the primary source for his work on this subject.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The seventh and eighth books of the Almagest would constitute a star catalogue of the names, positions, and magnitudes of over a thousand stars that Ptolemy placed into the traditional classification of 48 constellations.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The most important of these were the twelve constellations that defined the zodiac.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Aristarchus also wrote a book *On the Sizes and Distances of the Sun and Moon*, which is his only work to have survived.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In this work, he calculated the sizes of the Sun and Moon, as well as their distances from the Earth in terms of Earth radii.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Shortly afterwards, Eratosthenes calculated the size of the Earth, providing a value for the Earth radii with 252,000 stades, which may be equivalent to 39,690 kilometers, rather close to the true figure of 40,120 kilometers.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Hipparchus wrote another book *On the Sizes and Distances of the Sun and Moon*, which has not survived.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Both Aristarchus and Hipparchus drastically underestimated the distance of the Sun from the Earth.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Geocentrism, the idea that the Earth was at the center of the Solar System (or even cosmos) and that the other heavenly bodies, including the Sun, Moon, and the planets revolved around it, was dominant in ancient Greece and ancient cosmographical systems more generally.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] However, various alternatives appeared at one time or another.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] For example, the Pythagorean astronomical system, as proposed by Philolaus in the 5th century BC, proposed that there was an unseen "Central Fire" (not to be confused with the Sun) around which all other bodies of the cosmos revolved.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Heraclides Ponticus posited a geo-heliocentric system, where the Sun rotated around the Earth, but all other bodies rotated around the Sun.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Finally, in the 3rd century BCE, Aristarchus of Samos (sometimes called the "Ancient Copernicus") was the first and only premodern figure to propose a truly heliocentric model of the Solar System, placing the Sun, not the Earth, at the center of the universe.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Plato and Eudoxus of Cnidus were both active in astronomical thought in the first half of the fourth century BC, and with them came a decisive shift in Greek astronomy.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The work of these two figures represents a shift from earlier stellar concerns, focusing on the study of the stars, to the study of the planet.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] A new two-sphere model of the Solar System was proposed, and, for the first time, explanations for planetary observations were posited in the form of geometric theories.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The two-sphere model posits that Heaven and Earth are a pair of concentric spheres.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] That is to say, that both Heaven and Earth are conceived of as a sphere which have the same center.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In this way, they resemble the structure of an (conceptually spherical) egg, with an outer sphere (the Heaven) encompassing an inner sphere (the Earth).
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The outer, celestial sphere contains the fixed stars as well as the Sun, Moon, and planets moving along its surface.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The inner terrestrial sphere is fixed in the center.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Out of this arises the concept of a "celestial equator", which is the same as the equator of the Earth, projected outward onto the celestial sphere.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The term "ecliptic" refers to the annual path of the Sun around the celestial sphere.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] This path is tilted 23° with respect to the celestial equator.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The two locations where the ecliptic and the celestial equator meet represent the equinoxes (in the spring and fall).
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The two points where the ecliptic is furthest away from the equator represents the solstices (summer and winter).
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Eudoxus of Cnidus lived and practiced astronomy in the first half of the fourth century BC.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] His works are lost and so information about him comes from secondary references in ancient texts.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] There is a group of fragments about astronomy in the fourth century BC known as the Eudoxus Papyrus, but it contains little relevant informations about the views of Eudoxus himself.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] According to Hipparchus in his commentary on Aratus, Eudoxus is thought to have written include one called *Mirror* and another called *Phaenomena*, though an *Oktaeteris* is pseudonymously attributed to him.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Another work, *On Speeds*, endeavored to understand the then-unpredictable motions of the planets.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] He began his work in Athens and Egypt, he went on to found a school in Cyzicus where he gained his reputation.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] His pupils include Menaechmus, credited as the inventor of the notion of conic sections, and Polemarchus, whose own pupil Callippus offered well-received modifications of the Eudoxan theory of homocentric spheres.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] He also contributed to the calendar and the parapegma literature.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Eudoxus' model of planetary motion survives as summarized by Aristotle (*Metaphysics* XII, 8) as well as the commentary of Simplicius on the *De caelo* of Aristotle, produced in the 6th century AD.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Eudoxus' model attempted to explain the planetary motions being observed.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The key means by which it did so was by saying the fixed stars were moved along one rotating sphere, whereas each of the planets moved along several nested rotated spheres each with their own speed and pole.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Eudoxus established a school of thought that prioritized the use of geometrical models to explain the apparent paths of the stars.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Some, however, noticed flaws in the system of Eudoxus.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Autolycus of Pitane observed that the Moon would be observed to be a different size when the observation was taken at different times.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] However, this contradicted the Eudoxan theory of homocentrics, since it did not allow for any variation in the distance between the Earth and the Moon.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] 190 BCE) responded to the problems in earlier astronomical theories, especially that of Eudoxus, by producing the theory of eccentrics and epicycles (and their deferents).
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] This was further elaborated on by Hipparchus in the second century BC and, later, by Ptolemy in the 2nd century AD.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] This model allowed for theory to account for changes in the distance between the Earth and other astral bodies.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] However, while Apollonius is often credited with developing this theory, some think that the evidence for this is tenuous.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Some evidence may tie in an earlier author, Archimedes, with knowledge of epicycles and eccentrics, and the Antikythera mechanism also appears to presuppose eccentrics and epicycles in the way it produces calculations.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Hipparchus was a substantial figure of Greek astronomy in the 2nd century BC.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] He compiled a star catalogue, according to Pliny the Elder observed a *nova* (new star), and discovered the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] He appears to have had substantial information about Babylonian astronomers; no indications of such knowledge of Babylonian astronomy exists for previous Greek authors.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] It is not known how he had access to this information and it is likely that knowledge of Babylonian astronomy among the successors of Hipparchus in later eras, such as Ptolemy, relied on Hipparchus for their information of it.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Hipparchus' observations allowed him to discover that the tropical year was slightly less than 365.25 days, whereas the sidereal year was slightly more than 365.25 days.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Hipparchus is now known to have been correct, although it is not clear how Hipparchus discovered this.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Claudius Ptolemy was a mathematician who worked in the city of Alexandria in Roman Egypt in the 2nd century AD, deeply examining the shape and motion of the Earth and other celestial bodies.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Ptolemy's most important work was the *Almagest* (also known as the *Mathematical Composition*) and he composed other works such as the *Hypotheses*, *Tetrabiblos*, *Handy Tables*, the *Canobic Inscription*, and other minor works.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The Greeks sought to explain how a model could explain the irregular motions of the heavenly bodies.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Ptolemy accepted and elaborated on the notion of eccentrics and epicycles to explain this phenomenon.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The eccentric is the posit that the observer is not located at the center of rotation.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The notion of an epicycle was to say that there was a circle of rotation around the Earth, but to reject the idea that the rotating body itself would be placed on that circle.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Instead, a smaller rotating circle would be placed on the larger circle rotating around the Earth, and this smaller circle is called a deferent.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The body itself rotates around the circle of the deferent, meanwhile the deferent as a whole would be rotating around the Earth.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] This would also enable an observer from the Earth to observe an irregular motion on the part of the astral body.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Eccentrics and epicycles are the two main tools of Ptolemaic astronomy, and Ptolemy demonstrated that the two were closely related.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In the case of the Sun, Ptolemy understood that its motion could be predicted either by an eccentric or by an epicycle.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Once celestial bodies other than the Sun were introduced to the model, such as the planets, it became more complex.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The models for Jupiter, Saturn, and Mars included the center of the circle, the equant point, the epicycle, and an observer from Earth to give perspective.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The discovery of this model was that the center of the Mercury and Venus epicycles must always be colinear with the Sun.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Bounded elongation is the angular distance of celestial bodies from the center of the universe.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Ptolemy's model of the cosmos and his studies landed him an important place in history in the development of modern-day science.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In the Ptolemaic system, the Earth was at the center of the universe with the Moon, the Sun, and five planets circling it.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The circle of fixed stars marked the outermost sphere of the universe and beyond that would be the philosophical "aether" realm.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The Earth was at the exact center of the cosmos.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The sphere carrying the Moon is described as the boundary between the corruptible and changing sublunary world and the incorruptible and unchanging Heavens above it.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Ptolemaic astronomy became standard in medieval western European and Islamic astronomy until it was displaced by Maraghan, heliocentric and Tychonic systems by the 16th century.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The first critical discussion of the Almagest is by Artemidorus in the late second or early third century, though he understood it poorly.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In the fourth century, Pappus of Alexandria and Theon of Alexandria composed commentaries or treatises on sections of the Almagest.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] These works, however, only sought to understand the Almagest as opposed to improving or building upon it.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] This changed in the fifth century with the Neoplatonist philosopher Proclus.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] His exposition of the Almagest displayed, unlike his predecessors, a detailed grasp of the technical details of Ptolemy's work.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Though Proclus criticized some elements of the Almagest, such as its suggestion of the existence of epicycles, he and future Neoplatonists believed astronomy was essential to theology and continued to read Ptolemy's works.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Students and successors of Proclus to continue working in the tradition of the Almagest included Hilarius of Antioch and Marinus.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] An ill-studied full-scale commentary on the Almagest was produced in the sixth century, and of interest to historians are the significant number of scholia to its margins and between columns by scribes copying the text in later centuries that further engage with the Almagest.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The author of the original commentary is, however, not known, as many plausible candidates studied in the astronomy of Ptolemy lived in this era, such as Eutocius of Ascalon and John Philoponus.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] Several Greco-Roman astrological treatises are also known to have been imported into India during the first few centuries of our era.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] The *Yavanajataka* ("Sayings of the Greeks") was translated from Greek to Sanskrit by Yavanesvara during the 2nd century, under the patronage of the Western Satrap Saka king Rudradaman I.
[src:astronomer/ancient-greek-astronomy] In addition to the authors named in the article, the following list of people who worked on mathematical astronomy or cosmology may be of interest.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy uses a variety of methods to uncover evidence of past practices including archaeology, anthropology, astronomy, statistics and probability, and history.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because these methods are diverse and use data from such different sources, integrating them into a coherent argument has been a long-term difficulty for archaeoastronomers.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy fills complementary niches in landscape archaeology and cognitive archaeology.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Material evidence and its connection to the sky can reveal how a wider landscape can be integrated into beliefs about the cycles of nature, such as Mayan astronomy and its relationship with agriculture.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Other examples which have brought together ideas of cognition and landscape include studies of the cosmic order embedded in the roads of settlements.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy can be applied to all cultures and all time periods.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The meanings of the sky vary from culture to culture; nevertheless there are scientific methods which can be applied across cultures when examining ancient beliefs.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is perhaps the need to balance the social and scientific aspects of archaeoastronomy which led Clive Ruggles to describe it as "a field with academic work of high quality at one end but uncontrolled speculation bordering on lunacy at the other".
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Two hundred years before John Michell wrote the above, there were no archaeoastronomers and there were no professional archaeologists, but there were astronomers and antiquarians.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Late in the nineteenth century astronomers such as Richard Proctor and Charles Piazzi Smyth investigated the astronomical orientations of the pyramids.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The term *archaeoastronomy* was advanced by Elizabeth Chesley Baity (following the suggestion of Euan MacKie) in 1973, but as a topic of study it may be much older, depending on how archaeoastronomy is defined.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Clive Ruggles says that Heinrich Nissen, working in the mid-nineteenth century was arguably the first archaeoastronomer.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Rolf Sinclair says that Norman Lockyer, working in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, could be called the 'father of archaeoastronomy'.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Euan MacKie would place the origin even later, stating: "...the genesis and modern flowering of archaeoastronomy must surely lie in the work of Alexander Thom in Britain between the 1930s and the 1970s".
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the 1960s the work of the engineer Alexander Thom and that of the astronomer Gerald Hawkins, who proposed that Stonehenge was a Neolithic computer, inspired new interest in the astronomical features of ancient sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The claims of Hawkins were largely dismissed, but this was not the case for Alexander Thom's work, whose survey results of megalithic sites hypothesized widespread practice of accurate astronomy in the British Isles.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Euan MacKie, recognizing that Thom's theories needed to be tested, excavated at the Kintraw standing stone site in Argyllshire in 1970 and 1971 to check whether the latter's prediction of an observation platform on the hill slope above the stone was correct.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] There was an artificial platform there and this apparent verification of Thom's long alignment hypothesis (Kintraw was diagnosed as an accurate winter solstice site) led him to check Thom's geometrical theories at the Cultoon stone circle in Islay, also with a positive result.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] MacKie therefore broadly accepted Thom's conclusions and published new prehistories of Britain.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In contrast a re-evaluation of Thom's fieldwork by Clive Ruggles argued that Thom's claims of high accuracy astronomy were not fully supported by the evidence.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Nevertheless, Thom's legacy remains strong, Edwin C.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The approach in the New World, where anthropologists began to consider more fully the role of astronomy in Amerindian civilizations, was markedly different.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] They had access to sources that the prehistory of Europe lacks such as ethnographies and the historical records of the early colonizers.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Following the pioneering example of Anthony Aveni, this allowed New World archaeoastronomers to make claims for motives which in the Old World would have been mere speculation.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The concentration on historical data led to some claims of high accuracy that were comparatively weak when compared to the statistically led investigations in Europe.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This came to a head at a meeting sponsored by the International Astronomical Union (IAU) in Oxford in 1981.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The methodologies and research questions of the participants were considered so different that the conference proceedings were published as two volumes.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Nevertheless, the conference was considered a success in bringing researchers together and Oxford conferences have continued every four or five years at locations around the world.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy has long been seen as an interdisciplinary field that uses written and unwritten evidence to study the astronomies of other cultures.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Reflecting Archaeoastronomy's development as an interdisciplinary subject, research in the field is conducted by investigators trained in a wide range of disciplines.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Only rarely did they describe their work as astronomical, and then only as a secondary category.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Both practicing archaeoastronomers and observers of the discipline approach it from different perspectives.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The reactions of professional archaeologists to archaeoastronomy have been decidedly mixed.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Some expressed incomprehension or even hostility, varying from a rejection by the archaeological mainstream of what they saw as an archaeoastronomical fringe to an incomprehension between the cultural focus of archaeologists and the quantitative focus of early archaeoastronomers.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Yet archaeologists have increasingly come to incorporate many of the insights from archaeoastronomy into archaeology textbooks and, as mentioned above, some students wrote archaeology dissertations on archaeoastronomical topics.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Since archaeoastronomers disagree so widely on the characterization of the discipline, they even dispute its name.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] All three major international scholarly associations relate archaeoastronomy to the study of culture, using the term *Astronomy in Culture* or a translation.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Michael Hoskin sees an important part of the discipline as fact-collecting, rather than theorizing, and proposed to label this aspect of the discipline *Archaeotopography.* Ruggles and Saunders proposed *Cultural Astronomy* as a unifying term for the various methods of studying folk astronomies.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Others have argued that astronomy is an inaccurate term, what are being studied are cosmologies and people who object to the use of logos have suggested adopting the Spanish *cosmovisión*.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] When debates polarise between techniques, the methods are often referred to by a colour code, based on the colours of the bindings of the two volumes from the first Oxford Conference, where the approaches were first distinguished.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Green (Old World) archaeoastronomers rely heavily on statistics and are sometimes accused of missing the cultural context of what is a social practice.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Brown (New World) archaeoastronomers in contrast have abundant ethnographic and historical evidence and have been described as 'cavalier' on matters of measurement and statistical analysis.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Finding a way to integrate various approaches has been a subject of much discussion since the early 1990s.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] There is no one way to do archaeoastronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The divisions between archaeoastronomers tend not to be between the physical scientists and the social scientists.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Instead, it tends to depend on the location and/or kind of data available to the researcher.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the Old World, there is little data but the sites themselves; in the New World, the sites were supplemented by ethnographic and historic data.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The effects of the isolated development of archaeoastronomy in different places can still often be seen in research today.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Research methods can be classified as falling into one of two approaches, though more recent projects often use techniques from both categories.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Green archaeoastronomy is named after the cover of the book *Archaeoastronomy in the Old World*.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is based primarily on statistics and is particularly apt for prehistoric sites where the social evidence is relatively scant compared to the historic period.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The basic methods were developed by Alexander Thom during his extensive surveys of British megalithic sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Thom wished to examine whether or not prehistoric peoples used high-accuracy astronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] He believed that by using horizon astronomy, observers could make estimates of dates in the year to a specific day.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The observation required finding a place where on a specific date the Sun set into a notch on the horizon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A common theme is a mountain that blocked the Sun, but on the right day would allow the tiniest fraction to re-emerge on the other side for a 'double sunset'.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The animation below shows two sunsets at a hypothetical site, one the day before the summer solstice and one at the summer solstice, which has a double sunset.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] To test this idea he surveyed hundreds of stone rows and circles.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Any individual alignment could indicate a direction by chance, but he planned to show that together the distribution of alignments was non-random, showing that there was an astronomical intent to the orientation of at least some of the alignments.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] His results indicated the existence of eight, sixteen, or perhaps even thirty-two approximately equal divisions of the year.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The two solstices, the two equinoxes and four cross-quarter days, days halfway between a solstice and the equinox were associated with the medieval Celtic calendar.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] While not all these conclusions have been accepted, it has had an enduring influence on archaeoastronomy, especially in Europe.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Euan MacKie has supported Thom's analysis, to which he added an archaeological context by comparing Neolithic Britain to the Mayan civilization to argue for a stratified society in this period.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] To test his ideas he conducted a couple of excavations at proposed prehistoric observatories in Scotland.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Kintraw is a site notable for its four-meter high standing stone.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Thom proposed that this was a foresight to a point on the distant horizon between Beinn Shianaidh and Beinn o'Chaolias on Jura.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This, Thom argued, was a notch on the horizon where a double sunset would occur at midwinter.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, from ground level, this sunset would be obscured by a ridge in the landscape, and the viewer would need to be raised by two meters: another observation platform was needed.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This was identified across a gorge where a platform was formed from small stones.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In contrast Clive Ruggles has argued that there are problems with the selection of data in Thom's surveys.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Others have noted that the accuracy of horizon astronomy is limited by variations in refraction near the horizon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The many records of native customs and beliefs made by Spanish chroniclers and ethnographic researchers means that brown archaeoastronomy is often associated with studies of astronomy in the Americas.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] One famous site where historical records have been used to interpret sites is Chichen Itza.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Rather than analyzing the site and seeing which targets appear popular, archaeoastronomers have instead examined the ethnographic records to see what features of the sky were important to the Mayans and then sought archaeological correlates.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] One example which could have been overlooked without historical records is the Mayan interest in the planet Venus.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This interest is attested to by the Dresden codex which contains tables with information about Venus's appearances in the sky.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] These cycles would have been of astrological and ritual significance as Venus was associated with Quetzalcoatl or Xolotl.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Associations of architectural features with settings of Venus can be found in Chichen Itza, Uxmal, and probably some other Mesoamerican sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Temple of the Warriors bears iconography depicting feathered serpents associated with Quetzalcoatl or Kukulcan.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This means that the building's alignment towards the place on the horizon where Venus first appears in the evening sky (when it coincides with the rainy season) may be meaningful.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, since both the date and the azimuth of this event change continuously, a solar interpretation of this orientation is much more likely.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Anthony Aveni claims that another building associated with the planet Venus in the form of Kukulcan, and the rainy season at Chichen Itza is the Caracol.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is a building with a circular tower and doors facing the cardinal directions.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The base faces the most northerly setting of Venus.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Additionally the pillars of a stylobate on the building's upper platform were painted black and red.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] These are colours associated with Venus as an evening and morning star.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However the windows in the tower seem to have been little more than slots, making them poor at letting light in, but providing a suitable place to view out.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles considered the interpretation that the Caracol is an observatory site was debated among specialists, meeting the second of their four levels of site credibility.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Aveni states that one of the strengths of the brown methodology is that it can explore astronomies invisible to statistical analysis and offers the astronomy of the Incas as another example.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The empire of the Incas was conceptually divided using *ceques*, radial routes emanating from the capital at Cusco.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In eastern Asia archaeoastronomy has developed from the history of astronomy and much archaeoastronomy is searching for material correlates of the historical record.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is due to the rich historical record of astronomical phenomena which, in China, stretches back into the Han dynasty, in the second century BC.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A criticism of this method is that it can be statistically weak.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Schaefer in particular has questioned how robust the claimed alignments in the Caracol are.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because of the wide variety of evidence, which can include artefacts as well as sites, there is no one way to practice archaeoastronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Despite this it is accepted that archaeoastronomy is not a discipline that sits in isolation.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because archaeoastronomy is an interdisciplinary field, whatever is being investigated should make sense both archaeologically and astronomically.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Studies are more likely to be considered sound if they use theoretical tools found in archaeology like analogy and homology and if they can demonstrate an understanding of accuracy and precision found in astronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Both quantitative analyses and interpretations based on ethnographic analogies and other contextual evidence have recently been applied in systematic studies of architectural orientations in the Maya area and in other parts of Mesoamerica.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because archaeoastronomy is about the many and various ways people interacted with the sky, there are a diverse range of sources giving information about astronomical practices.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A common source of data for archaeoastronomy is the study of alignments.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is based on the assumption that the axis of alignment of an archaeological site is meaningfully oriented towards an astronomical target.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Brown archaeoastronomers may justify this assumption through reading historical or ethnographic sources, while green archaeoastronomers tend to prove that alignments are unlikely to be selected by chance, usually by demonstrating common patterns of alignment at multiple sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] An alignment is calculated by measuring the azimuth, the angle from north, of the structure and the altitude of the horizon it faces The azimuth is usually measured using a theodolite or a compass.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A compass is easier to use, though the deviation of the Earth's magnetic field from true north, known as its magnetic declination must be taken into account.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Compasses are also unreliable in areas prone to magnetic interference, such as sites being supported by scaffolding.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Additionally a compass can only measure the azimuth to a precision of a half a degree.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A theodolite can be considerably more accurate if used correctly, but it is also considerably more difficult to use correctly.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] There is no inherent way to align a theodolite with North and so the scale has to be calibrated using astronomical observation, usually the position of the Sun.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because the position of celestial bodies changes with the time of day due to the Earth's rotation, the time of these calibration observations must be accurately known, or else there will be a systematic error in the measurements.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Horizon altitudes can be measured with a theodolite or a clinometer.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For artifacts such as the Sky Disc of Nebra, alleged to be a Bronze Age artefact depicting the cosmos, the analysis would be similar to typical post-excavation analysis as used in other sub-disciplines in archaeology.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] An artefact is examined and attempts are made to draw analogies with historical or ethnographical records of other peoples.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The more parallels that can be found, the more likely an explanation is to be accepted by other archaeologists.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A more mundane example is the presence of astrological symbols found on some shoes and sandals from the Roman Empire.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The use of shoes and sandals is well known, but Carol van Driel-Murray has proposed that astrological symbols etched onto sandals gave the footwear spiritual or medicinal meanings.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is supported through citation of other known uses of astrological symbols and their connection to medical practice and with the historical records of the time.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Another well-known artefact with an astronomical use is the Antikythera mechanism.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In this case analysis of the artefact, and reference to the description of similar devices described by Cicero, would indicate a plausible use for the device.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The argument is bolstered by the presence of symbols on the mechanism, allowing the disc to be read.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Art and inscriptions may not be confined to artefacts, but also appear painted or inscribed on an archaeological site.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Sometimes inscriptions are helpful enough to give instructions to a site's use.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For example, a Greek inscription on a stele (from Itanos) has been translated as:"Patron set this up for Zeus Epopsios.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Should anyone wish to know: off 'the little pig' and the stele the sun turns." From Mesoamerica come Mayan and Aztec codices.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] These are folding books made from Amatl, processed tree bark on which are glyphs in Mayan or Aztec script.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Dresden codex contains information regarding the Venus cycle, confirming its importance to the Mayans.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] More problematic are those cases where the movement of the Sun at different times and seasons causes light and shadow interactions with petroglyphs.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A widely known example is the Sun Dagger of Fajada Butte at which a glint of sunlight passes over a spiral petroglyph.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The location of a dagger of light on the petroglyph varies throughout the year.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] At the summer solstice a dagger can be seen through the heart of the spiral; at the winter solstice two daggers appear to either side of it.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is proposed that this petroglyph was created to mark these events.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Recent studies have identified many similar sites in the US Southwest and Northwestern Mexico.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It has been argued that the number of solstitial markers at these sites provides statistical evidence that they were intended to mark the solstices.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Sun Dagger site on Fajada Butte in Chaco Canyon, New Mexico, stands out for its explicit light markings that record all the key events of both the solar and lunar cycles: summer solstice, winter solstice, equinox, and the major and minor lunar standstills of the Moon's 18.6 year cycle.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In addition at two other sites on Fajada Butte, there are five light markings on petroglyphs recording the summer and winter solstices, equinox and solar noon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Numerous buildings and interbuilding alignments of the great houses of Chaco Canyon and outlying areas are oriented to the same solar and lunar directions that are marked at the Sun Dagger site.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] If no ethnographic nor historical data are found which can support this assertion then acceptance of the idea relies upon whether or not there are enough petroglyph sites in North America that such a correlation could occur by chance.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is helpful when petroglyphs are associated with existing peoples.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This allows ethnoastronomers to question informants as to the meaning of such symbols.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] As well as the materials left by peoples themselves, there are also the reports of other who have encountered them.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The historical records of the Conquistadores are a rich source of information about the pre-Columbian Americans.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnographers also provide material about many other peoples.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Anthony Aveni uses the importance of zenith passages as an example of the importance of ethnography.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For peoples living between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn there are two days of the year when the noon Sun passes directly overhead and casts no shadow.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In parts of Mesoamerica this was considered a significant day as it would herald the arrival of rains, and so play a part in the cycle of agriculture.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This knowledge is still considered important amongst Mayan Indians living in Central America today.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The ethnographic records suggested to archaeoastronomers that this day may have been important to the ancient Mayans.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] There are also shafts known as 'zenith tubes' which illuminate subterranean rooms when the Sun passes overhead found at places like Monte Albán and Xochicalco.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is only through the ethnography that we can speculate that the timing of the illumination was considered important in Mayan society.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Alignments to the sunrise and sunset on the day of the zenith passage have been claimed to exist at several sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, it has been shown that, since there are very few orientations that can be related to these phenomena, they likely have different explanations.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnographies also caution against over-interpretation of sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] At a site in Chaco Canyon can be found a pictograph with a star, crescent and hand.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It has been argued by some astronomers that this is a record of the 1054 Supernova.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However recent reexaminations of related 'supernova petroglyphs' raises questions about such sites in general.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Cotte and Ruggles used the Supernova petroglyph as an example of a completely refuted site and anthropological evidence suggests other interpretations.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Zuni people, who claim a strong ancestral affiliation with Chaco, marked their sun-watching station with a crescent, star, hand and sundisc, similar to those found at the Chaco site.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnoastronomy is also an important field outside of the Americas.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For example, anthropological work with Aboriginal Australians is producing much information about their Indigenous astronomies and about their interaction with the modern world.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Once the researcher has data to test, it is often necessary to attempt to recreate ancient sky conditions to place the data in its historical environment.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] To calculate what astronomical features a structure faced, a coordinate system is needed, and the stars provide such a system.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] On a clear night observe the stars spinning around the celestial pole can be observed.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This point is +90° of the North Celestial Pole or −90° observing the Southern Celestial Pole.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The concentric circles the stars trace out are lines of celestial latitude, known as *declination*.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The arc connecting the points on the horizon due East and due West (if the horizon is flat) and all points midway between the Celestial Poles is the Celestial Equator which has a declination of 0°.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The visible declinations vary depending where you are on the globe.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Only an observer on the North Pole of Earth would be unable to see any stars from the Southern Celestial Hemisphere at night (see diagram below).
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Once a declination has been found for the point on the horizon that a building faces it is then possible to say whether a specific body can be seen in that direction.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] While the stars are fixed to their declinations the Sun is not.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The rising point of the Sun varies throughout the year.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It swings between two limits marked by the solstices a bit like a pendulum, slowing as it reaches the extremes, but passing rapidly through the midpoint.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] If an archaeoastronomer can calculate from the azimuth and horizon height that a site was built to view a declination of +23.5° then he or she need not wait until 21 June to confirm the site does indeed face the summer solstice.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For more information see History of solar observation.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Moon's appearance is considerably more complex.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Its motion, like the Sun, is between two limits—known as *luni*stices rather than *sol*stices.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, its travel between lunistices is considerably faster.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It takes a sidereal month to complete its cycle rather than the year-long trek of the Sun.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is further complicated as the lunistices marking the limits of the Moon's movement move on an 18.6 year cycle.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For slightly over nine years the extreme limits of the Moon are outside the range of sunrise.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For the remaining half of the cycle the Moon never exceeds the limits of the range of sunrise.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, much lunar observation was concerned with the *phase* of the Moon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The cycle from one New Moon to the next runs on an entirely different cycle, the Synodic month.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Thus when examining sites for lunar significance the data can appear sparse due to the extremely variable nature of the Moon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Finally there is often a need to correct for the apparent movement of the stars.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] On the timescale of human civilisation the stars have largely maintained the same position relative to each other.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Each night they appear to rotate around the celestial poles due to the Earth's rotation about its axis.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, the Earth spins rather like a spinning top.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Not only does the Earth rotate, it wobbles.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Earth's axis takes around 25,800 years to complete one full wobble.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The effect to the archaeoastronomer is that stars did not rise over the horizon in the past in the same places as they do today.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Nor did the stars rotate around Polaris as they do now.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The movement of the Earth's axis was already noticed by the Sumerians over six thousand years ago, when they were able to observe the star Canopus culminating directly above the horizon on the southern meridian for the first time in their oldest and southernmost city Eridu.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For several decades, Canopus was not yet visible in the neighbouring town of Ur to the north-east of Eridu, and therefore, it was called the "Star of the City of Eridu" in Sumerian.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the case of the Egyptian pyramids, it has been shown they were aligned towards Thuban, a faint star in the constellation of Draco.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The effect can be substantial over relatively short lengths of time, historically speaking.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] For instance a person born on 25 December in Roman times would have been born with the Sun in the constellation Capricorn.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the modern period a person born on the same date would have the Sun in Sagittarius due to the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Additionally there are often transient phenomena, events which do not happen on an annual cycle.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Most predictable are events like eclipses.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the case of solar eclipses these can be used to date events in the past.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A solar eclipse mentioned by Herodotus enables us to date a battle between the Medes and the Lydians, which following the eclipse failed to happen, to 28 May, 585 BC.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Some comets are predictable, most famously Halley's Comet.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Yet as a class of object they remain unpredictable and can appear at any time.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Some have extremely lengthy orbital periods which means their past appearances and returns cannot be predicted.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Others may have only ever passed through the Solar System once and so are inherently unpredictable.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Meteor showers should be predictable, but some meteors are cometary debris and so require calculations of orbits which are currently impossible to complete.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Other events noted by ancients include aurorae, sun dogs and rainbows all of which are as impossible to predict as the ancient weather, but nevertheless may have been considered important phenomena.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A common justification for the need for astronomy is the need to develop an accurate calendar for agricultural reasons.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ancient texts like Hesiod's Works and Days, an ancient farming manual, would appear to partially confirm this: astronomical observations are used in combination with ecological signs, such as bird migrations to determine the seasons.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnoastronomical studies of the Hopi of the southwestern United States indicate that they carefully observed the rising and setting positions of the Sun to determine the proper times to plant crops.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, ethnoastronomical work with the Mursi of Ethiopia shows that their luni-solar calendar was somewhat haphazard, indicating the limits of astronomical calendars in some societies.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] All the same, calendars appear to be an almost universal phenomenon in societies as they provide tools for the regulation of communal activities.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] One such example is the *Tzolk'in* calendar of 260 days.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Together with the 365-day year, it was used in pre-Columbian Mesoamerica, forming part of a comprehensive calendrical system, which combined a series of astronomical observations and ritual cycles.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomical studies throughout Mesoamerica have shown that the orientations of most structures refer to the Sun and were used in combination with the 260-day cycle for scheduling agricultural activities and the accompanying rituals.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The distribution of dates and intervals marked by orientations of monumental ceremonial complexes in the area along the southern Gulf Coast in Mexico, dated to about 1100 to 700 BCE, represents the earliest evidence of the use of this cycle.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Other peculiar calendars include ancient Greek calendars.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] These were nominally lunar, starting with the New Moon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In reality the calendar could pause or skip days with confused citizens inscribing dates by both the civic calendar and *ton theoi*, by the moon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The lack of any universal calendar for ancient Greece suggests that coordination of panhellenic events such as games or rituals could be difficult and that astronomical symbolism may have been used as a politically neutral form of timekeeping.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Orientation measurements in Greek temples and Byzantine churches have been associated to deity's name day, festivities, and special events.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Another motive for studying the sky is to understand and explain the universe.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In these cultures myth was a tool for achieving this, and the explanations, while not reflecting the standards of modern science, are cosmologies.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Incas arranged their empire to demonstrate their cosmology.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The capital, Cusco, was at the centre of the empire and connected to it by means of ceques, conceptually straight lines radiating out from the centre.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] These ceques connected the centre of the empire to the four *suyus*, which were regions defined by their direction from Cusco.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The notion of a quartered cosmos is common across the Andes.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Gary Urton, who has conducted fieldwork in the Andean villagers of Misminay, has connected this quartering with the appearance of the Milky Way in the night sky.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In one season it will bisect the sky and in another bisect it in a perpendicular fashion.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The importance of observing cosmological factors is also seen on the other side of the world.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Forbidden City in Beijing is laid out to follow cosmic order though rather than observing four directions.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Chinese system was composed of five directions: North, South, East, West and Centre.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Forbidden City occupied the centre of ancient Beijing.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] One approaches the Emperor from the south, thus placing him in front of the circumpolar stars.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] This creates the situation of the heavens revolving around the person of the Emperor.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Chinese cosmology is now better known through its export as feng shui.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] There is also much information about how the universe was thought to work stored in the mythology of the constellations.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Barasana of the Amazon plan part of their annual cycle based on observation of the stars.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] When their constellation of the Caterpillar-Jaguar (roughly equivalent to the modern Scorpius) falls they prepare to catch the pupating caterpillars of the forest as they fall from the trees.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The caterpillars provide food at a season when other foods are scarce.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Northern Dene peoples of Alaska and northwestern Canada recognize Traveller constellations that incorporate large portions of the night sky.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] These constellations represent a culture hero known as the Traveller who, according to oral tradition, journeyed around the world before his spirit became embodied in the stars.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The constellations are composed of multiple smaller star groups named using body-part terminology, with the Milky Way identified as the Traveller's trail.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Knowledge of these constellations is traditionally acquired through personal discovery rather than direct instruction, and they serve roles in navigation, timekeeping, and spiritual practice.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] A more well-known source of constellation myth are the texts of the Greeks and Romans.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The origin of their constellations remains a matter of vigorous and occasionally fractious debate.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The loss of one of the sisters, Merope, in some Greek myths may reflect an astronomical event wherein one of the stars in the Pleiades disappeared from view by the naked eye.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The chaos, monsters and violence in ancient myths are representative of the forces that shape each age.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] They argued that ancient myths are the remains of preliterate, late Neolithic astronomy that was lost.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Santillana and von Dechend argued in their book *Hamlet's Mill: An Essay on Myth and the Frame of Time* (1969) that ancient myths have no historical or factual basis other than a cosmological one encoding astronomical phenomena, especially the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Santillana and von Dechend's approach is not widely accepted.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] By including celestial motifs in clothing it becomes possible for the wearer to make claims the power on Earth is drawn from above.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] It has been said that the Shield of Achilles described by Homer is also a catalogue of constellations.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In North America shields depicted in Comanche petroglyphs appear to include Venus symbolism.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Solsticial alignments also can be seen as displays of power.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] When viewed from a ceremonial plaza on the Island of the Sun (the mythical origin place of the Sun) in Lake Titicaca, the Sun was seen to rise at the June solstice between two towers on a nearby ridge.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The sacred part of the island was separated from the remainder of it by a stone wall and ethnographic records indicate that access to the sacred space was restricted to members of the Inca ruling elite.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ordinary pilgrims stood on a platform outside the ceremonial area to see the solstice Sun rise between the towers.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In Egypt the temple of Amun-Re at Karnak has been the subject of much study.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] Evaluation of the site, taking into account the change over time of the obliquity of the ecliptic show that the Great Temple was aligned on the rising of the midwinter Sun.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] The length of the corridor down which sunlight would travel would have limited illumination at other times of the year.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p01] In a later period the Serapeum of Alexandria was also said to have contained a solar alignment so that, on a specific sunrise, a shaft of light would pass across the lips of the statue of Serapis thus symbolising the Sun saluting the god.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Clive Ruggles and Michel Cotte recently edited a book on heritage sites of astronomy and archaeoastronomy which discussed a worldwide sample of astronomical and archaeoastronomical sites and provided criteria for the classification of archaeoastronomical sites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Newgrange is a passage tomb in the Republic of Ireland dating from around 3,300 to 2,900 BC For a few days around the Winter Solstice light shines along the central passageway into the heart of the tomb.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] What makes this notable is not that light shines in the passageway, but that it does not do so through the main entrance.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Instead it enters via a hollow box above the main doorway discovered by Michael O'Kelly.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] It is this roofbox which strongly indicates that the tomb was built with an astronomical aspect in mind.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles gave Newgrange as an example of a Generally accepted site, the highest of their four levels of credibility.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Since the first modern measurements of the precise cardinal orientations of the Giza pyramids by Flinders Petrie, various astronomical methods have been proposed for the original establishment of these orientations.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] It was recently proposed that this was done by observing the positions of two stars in the Plough / Big Dipper which was known to Egyptians as the thigh.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] It is thought that a vertical alignment between these two stars checked with a plumb bob was used to ascertain where north lay.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The deviations from true north using this model reflect the accepted dates of construction.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Some have argued that the pyramids were laid out as a map of the three stars in the belt of Orion, although this theory has been criticized by reputable astronomers.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The site was instead probably governed by a spectacular hierophany which occurs at the summer solstice, when the Sun, viewed from the Sphinx terrace, forms—together with the two giant pyramids—the symbol Akhet, which was also the name of the Great Pyramid.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Further, the south east corners of all the three pyramids align towards the temple of Heliopolis, as first discovered by the Egyptologist Mark Lehner.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The astronomical ceiling of the tomb of Senenmut (c.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] 1470 BC) contains the Celestial Diagram depicting circumpolar constellations in the form of discs.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Each disc is divided into 24 sections suggesting a 24-hour time period.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Constellations are portrayed as sacred deities of Egypt.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The observation of lunar cycles is also evident.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] El Castillo, also known as Kukulcán's Pyramid, is a Mesoamerican step-pyramid built in the centre of Mayan center of Chichen Itza in Mexico.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Several architectural features have suggested astronomical elements.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Each of the stairways built into the sides of the pyramid has 91 steps.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Along with the extra one for the platform at the top, this totals 365 steps, which is possibly one for each day of the year (365.25) or the number of lunar orbits in 10,000 rotations (365.01).
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] A visually striking effect is seen every March and September as an unusual shadow occurs around the equinoxes.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Light and shadow phenomena have been proposed to explain a possible architectural hierophany involving the sun at Chichén Itzá in a Maya Toltec structure dating to about 1000 CE.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] A shadow appears to descend the west balustrade of the northern stairway.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The visual effect is of a serpent descending the stairway, with its head at the base in light.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Additionally the western face points to sunset around 25 May, traditionally the date of transition from the dry to the rainy season.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The intended alignment was, however, likely incorporated in the northern (main) facade of the temple, as it corresponds to sunsets on May 20 and July 24, recorded also by the central axis of Castillo at Tulum.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The two dates are separated by 65 and 300 days, and it has been shown that the solar orientations in Mesoamerica regularly correspond to dates separated by calendrically significant intervals (multiples of 13 and 20 days).
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles used the "equinox hierophany" at Chichén Itzá as an example of an Unproven site, the third of their four levels of credibility.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Many astronomical alignments have been claimed for Stonehenge, a complex of megaliths and earthworks in the Salisbury Plain of England.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The most famous of these is the midsummer alignment, where the Sun rises over the Heel Stone.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] However, this interpretation has been challenged by some archaeologists who argue that the midwinter alignment, where the viewer is outside Stonehenge and sees the Sun setting in the henge, is the more significant alignment, and the midsummer alignment may be a coincidence due to local topography.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles gave Stonehenge as an example of a Generally accepted site, the highest of their four levels of credibility.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] As well as solar alignments, there are proposed lunar alignments.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The four station stones mark out a rectangle.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The short sides point towards the midsummer sunrise and midwinter sunset.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The long sides if viewed towards the south-east, face the most southerly rising of the Moon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Anthony Aveni notes that these lunar alignments have never gained the acceptance that the solar alignments have received.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] This is an architecturally outstanding Neolithic chambered tomb on the mainland of Orkney, Scotland—probably dating to the early 3rd millennium BC, and where the setting Sun at midwinter shines down the entrance passage into the central chamber (see Newgrange).
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In the 1990s further investigations were carried out to discover whether this was an accurate or an approximate solar alignment.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Several new aspects of the site were discovered.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In the first place the entrance passage faces the hills of the island Hoy, about 10 miles away.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Secondly, it consists of two straight lengths, angled at a few degrees to each other.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Thirdly, the outer part is aligned towards the midwinter sunset position on a level horizon just to the left of Ward Hill on Hoy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Fourthly the inner part points directly at the Barnhouse standing stone about 400m away and then to the right end of the summit of Ward Hill, just before it dips down to the notch between it at Cuilags to the right.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] This indicated line points to sunset on the first Sixteenths of the solar year (according to A.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Thom) before and after the winter solstice and the notch at the base of the right slope of the Hill is at the same declination.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Fourthly a similar 'double sunset' phenomenon is seen at the right end of Cuilags, also on Hoy; here the date is the first Eighth of the year before and after the winter solstice, at the beginning of November and February respectively—the Old Celtic festivals of Samhain and Imbolc.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] This alignment is not indicated by an artificial structure but gains plausibility from the other two indicated lines.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Maeshowe is thus an extremely sophisticated calendar site which must have been positioned carefully in order to use the horizon foresights in the ways described.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Uxmal is a Mayan city in the Puuc Hills of Yucatán Peninsula, Mexico.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Governor's Palace at Uxmal is often used as an exemplar of why it is important to combine ethnographic and alignment data.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The palace is aligned with an azimuth of 118° on the pyramid of Cehtzuc.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] This alignment corresponds approximately to the southernmost rising and, with a much greater precision, to the northernmost setting of Venus; both phenomena occur once every eight years.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] By itself this would not be sufficient to argue for a meaningful connection between the two events.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The palace has to be aligned in one direction or another and why should the rising of Venus be any more important than the rising of the Sun, Moon, other planets, Sirius *et cetera*?
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The answer given is that not only does the palace point towards significant points of Venus, it is also covered in glyphs which stand for Venus and Mayan zodiacal constellations.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Moreover, the great northerly extremes of Venus always occur in late April or early May, coinciding with the onset of the rainy season.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Venus glyphs placed in the cheeks of the Maya rain god Chac, most likely referring to the concomitance of these phenomena, support the west-working orientation scheme.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In Chaco Canyon, the center of the ancient Pueblo culture in the American Southwest, numerous solar and lunar light markings and architectural and road alignments have been documented.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] These findings date to the 1977 discovery of the Sun Dagger site by Anna Sofaer.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Three large stone slabs leaning against a cliff channel light and shadow markings onto two spiral petroglyphs on the cliff wall, marking the solstices, equinoxes and the lunar standstills of the 18.6 year cycle of the moon.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Subsequent research by the Solstice Project and others demonstrated that numerous building and interbuilding alignments of the great houses of Chaco Canyon are oriented to solar, lunar and cardinal directions.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In addition, research shows that the Great North Road, a thirty-five mile engineered "road", was constructed not for utilitarian purposes but rather to connect the ceremonial center of Chaco Canyon with the direction north.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] In recent years, new research has suggested that the Lascaux cave paintings in France may incorporate prehistoric star charts.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Michael Rappenglueck of LMU Munich argues that some of the non-figurative dot clusters and dots within some of the figurative images correlate with the constellations of Taurus, the Pleiades and the grouping known as the "Summer Triangle".
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Applying phylogenetics to myths of the Cosmic Hunt, Julien d'Huy suggested that the palaeolithic version of this story could be the following: there is an animal that is a horned herbivore, especially an elk.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The animal is alive when it is transformed into a constellation.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Archaeoastronomy owes something of a poor reputation among scholars due to its occasional misuse to advance a range of pseudo-historical accounts.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Reuter compiled a study entitled *Germanische Himmelskunde*, or "Teutonic Skylore".
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The astronomical orientations of ancient monuments claimed by Reuter and his followers would place the ancient Germanic peoples ahead of the Ancient Near East in the field of astronomy, demonstrating the intellectual superiority of the "Aryans" (Indo-Europeans) over the Semites.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Fell interpreted inscriptions in West Virginia as a description in Celtic Ogham alphabet of the supposed winter solstitial marker at the site.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The controversial translation was supposedly validated by a problematic archaeoastronomical indication in which the winter solstice Sun shone on an inscription of the Sun at the site.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Subsequent analyses criticized its cultural inappropriateness, as well as its linguistic and archaeoastronomical claims, to describe it as an example of "cult archaeology".
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Archaeoastronomy is sometimes related to the fringe discipline of Archaeocryptography, when its followers attempt to find underlying mathematical orders beneath the proportions, size, and placement of archaeoastronomical sites such as Stonehenge and the Pyramid of Kukulcán at Chichen Itza.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Since the 19th century, numerous scholars have sought to use archaeoastronomical calculations to demonstrate the antiquity of Ancient Indian Vedic culture, computing the dates of astronomical observations ambiguously described in ancient poetry to as early as 4000 BC.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] David Pingree, a historian of Indian astronomy, condemned "the scholars who perpetrate wild theories of prehistoric science and call themselves archaeoastronomers".
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] There are currently several academic organisations for scholars of archaeoastronomy (including ethnoastronomy and Indigenous astronomy).
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] ISAAC – the International Society for Archaeoastronomy and Astronomy in Culture – was founded in 1996 as the global society for the field.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] It sponsors the Oxford conferences and the Journal of Astronomy in Culture.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] SEAC – La Société Européenne pour l'Astronomie dans la Culture – was founded in 1992 with a focus on broader Europe.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] SEAC holds annual conferences in Europe and publishes refereed conference proceedings on an annual basis.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] SIAC – La Sociedad Interamericana de Astronomía en la Cultura was founded in 2003 with a focus on Latin America.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] SCAAS - The Society for Cultural Astronomy in the American Southwest was founded in 2009 as a regional organisation focusing on the astronomies of the native peoples of the Southwestern United States; it has since held seven meetings and workshops.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] AAAC – the Australian Association for Astronomy in Culture was founded in 2020 in Australia, focusing on Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander astronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Romanian Society for Cultural Astronomy was founded in 2019, holding an annual international conference and publishing the first monograph on archaeo- and ethnoastronomy in Romania (2019).
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] SMART – the Society of Māori Astronomy Research and Traditions was founded in Aotearoa/New Zealand in 2013, focusing on Maori astronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Native Skywatchers was founded in 2007 in Minnesota, USA to promote Native American star knowledge, particularly of the Lakota and Ojibwe peoples of the northern US and Canada.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] Additionally the *Journal for the History of Astronomy* publishes many archaeoastronomical papers.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] For twenty-seven volumes (from 1979 to 2002) it published an annual supplement *Archaeoastronomy*.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The *Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage*, *Culture & Cosmos*, and the *Journal of Skyscape Archaeology* also publish papers on archaeoastronomy.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] National projects and university programs including, or dedicated to, cultural astronomy are found globally.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Sophia Centre for Cosmology in Culture at the University of Wales - Trinity Saint David in Lampeter, UK.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Cultural Astronomy Program at the University of Melbourne in Australia.
[src:astronomer/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Tata Institute of Fundamental Research made interesting findings in this field.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] An **astronomer** is a scientist in the field of astronomy who focuses on a specific question or field outside the scope of Earth.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Astronomers study astronomical objects, such as stars, planets, moons, comets and galaxies, by some combination of observation and the application of astrophysical models.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Examples of topics or fields astronomers study include planetary science, solar astronomy, the origin or evolution of stars, or the formation of galaxies.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] A related but distinct subject is physical cosmology, which studies the universe as a whole.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Astronomers cannot typically perform experiments: the objects of interest in the field are far away.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Consequently they rely primarily on observations, collecting electromagnetic radiation, gravitational waves, or particles such as cosmic rays.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Some experiments on planets in the solar system are now possible via remote controlled spacecraft.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Some of the measurements astronomers perform include astrometry (positions of celestial bodies), photometry (light flux), spectroscopy (intensity vs wavelength), and imaging.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Astronomy includes astrometry, planetary astronomy, astrophysics, astrochemistry, astrobiology, stellar astronomy, galactic astronomy, extragalactic astronomy, and physical cosmology.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Astronomers can also specialize in certain specialties of observational astronomy, such as infrared astronomy, neutrino astronomy, x-ray astronomy, and gravitational-wave astronomy.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Historically, astronomy was more concerned with the classification and description of phenomena in the sky, while astrophysics attempted to explain these phenomena and the differences between them using physical laws.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Today, that distinction has mostly disappeared and the terms "astronomer" and "astrophysicist" are interchangeable.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Professional astronomers are highly educated individuals who typically have a PhD in physics or astronomy and are employed by research institutions or universities.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] They spend the majority of their time working on research, although they quite often have other duties such as teaching, building instruments, or aiding in the operation of an observatory.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] The American Astronomical Society, which is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America, has approximately 8,200 members (as of 2024).
[src:astronomer/astronomer] This number includes scientists from other fields such as physics, geology, and engineering, whose research interests are closely related to astronomy.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] The International Astronomical Union comprises about 12,700 members from 92 countries who are involved in astronomical research at the PhD level and beyond (as of 2024).
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Contrary to the classical image of an old astronomer peering through a telescope through the dark hours of the night, it is far more common to use a charge-coupled device (CCD) camera to record a long, deep exposure, allowing a more sensitive image to be created because the light is added over time.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Before CCDs, photographic plates were a common method of observation.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Modern astronomers spend relatively little time at telescopes, usually just a few weeks per year.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Analysis of observed phenomena, along with making predictions as to the causes of what they observe, takes the majority of observational astronomers' time.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Astronomers who serve as faculty spend much of their time teaching undergraduate and graduate classes.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Most universities also have outreach programs, including public telescope time and sometimes planetarium, as a public service to encourage interest in the field.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Those who become astronomers usually have a broad background in physics, mathematics, sciences, and computing in high school.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Taking courses that teach how to research, write, and present papers are part of the higher education of an astronomer, while most astronomers attain both a Master's degree and eventually a PhD degree in astronomy, physics or astrophysics.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Throughout the PhD training, a successful student is financially supported with a stipend.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] While there is a relatively low number of professional astronomers, the field is popular among amateurs.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] Most cities have amateur astronomy clubs that meet on a regular basis and often host star parties.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] The Astronomical Society of the Pacific is the largest general astronomical society in the world, comprising both professional and amateur astronomers as well as educators from 70 different nations.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] As with any hobby, most people who practice amateur astronomy may devote a few hours a month to stargazing and reading the latest developments in research.
[src:astronomer/astronomer] However, amateurs span the range from so-called "armchair astronomers" to people who own science-grade telescopes and instruments with which they are able to make their own discoveries, create astrophotographs, and assist professional astronomers in research.
